04592nam a22006375i 9780774827317DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748273177 a10.59962/97807748273172doi  a(DE-B1597)661048  a(OCoLC)875729262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1035.M87 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a305.6/9709712231 aKazemipur, Abdolmohammad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Muslim Question in Canada :bA Story of Segmented Integration /cAbdolmohammad Kazemipur. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b65 graphs, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tContext -- tMuslims and/in the West -- tResponses to the Muslim Question -- tConceptual Framework -- tThe Fundamentals -- tCanadian Immigration and Muslim Immigrants -- tMuslims in Canada: Front Stage -- tCanadian Muslim Lives -- tThe Muslim Question in Canada -- tMuslims in Canada: Back Stage -- tMuslims at Work -- tBeyond the Friendly Smiles -- tSolutions -- tConclusions and Implications -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo those who study the integration of immigrants in Western countries, both Muslims and Canada are seen to be exceptions to the rule. Muslims are often perceived as unable or unwilling to integrate, mostly due to their religious beliefs; Canada is portrayed as a model for successful integration. This book addresses the intersection of these two types of exceptionalism through an empirical study of the experiences of Muslims in Canada. Drawing on data from large-scale surveys as well as face-to-face interviews, Kazemipur draws a detailed picture of four major domains of immigrant integration: institutional, media, economic, and social/communal. His findings indicate that the integration of Muslims in Canada is not problematic in the institutional and media domains. However, there are serious problems the economic and social domains, which need to be addressed. A fresh account of the lives and experiences of Muslim immigrants in Canada, this book gets at the roots of the so-called Muslim question in Canada. Replete with practical implications, the analysis shows that instead of fixating on religion, the focus should be on economic and social challenges faced by Muslims in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada -- Emigration and immigration -- Social aspects. 0aImmigrantszCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aImmigrantszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aMuslims -- Canada -- Economic conditions. 0aMuslims -- Canada -- Social conditions. 0aMuslims -- Cultural assimilation -- Canada. 0aMuslimsxCultural assimilationzCanada. 0aMuslimszCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aMuslimszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482731740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774827317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774827317/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles